  <h2>What are surplus funds — and why do they exist?</h2>
  <p>Most people have never heard of surplus funds. That's exactly why so much money goes unclaimed.</p>
  <div class="grid2">
    <div class="card"><h3>How it happens</h3><p>When a lender forecloses on a home, it gets auctioned to the highest bidder. The lender only takes what they're owed. Any money above that is called "surplus funds" — and it legally belongs to the former homeowner.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h3>Where does it go?</h3><p>The surplus is deposited with the county court or a government agency. It sits there — sometimes for years — waiting to be claimed. If nobody claims it, the government eventually keeps it.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h3>Why don't people know?</h3><p>Notification laws vary by state. Many homeowners are never properly told. They're already dealing with the trauma of losing their home — the last thing they expect is a check waiting for them.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h3>Is this legal?</h3><p>100% legal. Surplus funds recovery is a legitimate, court-recognized process. The money is yours by law. All we're doing is making sure you get what you're already owed.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="math-box-wrap">
